reply_content:
@o@ogee2863 You’ve hit the nail on the head, and it only confirms what I’ve been saying. If Newcastle are supposed to be a “small club”, then it’s frankly embarrassing for a Man Utd fan to watch their team at Old Trafford on Boxing Day dig in for an entire second half and live off counter-attacks.

Newcastle weren’t even pressing hard - Man Utd just dropped deep and stopped playing. If clubs like PSG, Barca, City, Real or Bayern did that at home, they’d be booed off. It says everything about where Man Utd are in the pecking order these days: miles off the top. And yes, it’s embarrassing.

I’ll bet you won’t see another Newcastle away game this season where they have 75% possession for a full half and completely run the show. I’d even argue Everton, despite losing 4–1, looked better than the Man Utd side we saw yesterday. This was a game Newcastle had to win - chances don’t come much bigger than this.

@ogee2863 Man Utd have become a thoroughly mediocre side. We saw it ourselves last season when Newcastle humiliated them on two occasions. And the fear of a repeat was plain to see in their extremely destructive approach to the second half on Friday. It’s hard to take you seriously when you’ve clearly only watched the highlights and haven’t experienced them sitting passively and waiting deep in their own half for an entire half. That some Man Utd fans accept this because a few players were missing (due to injuries and AFCON - yet still fewer in total than Newcastle have on their injury list) only shows how far the club has sunk over recent seasons.

It must really hurt you painfully to watch Newcastle, with many injuries, grind through the first half of the season playing roughly every 3-4 days because of the League Cup and Champions League matches - matches Man Utd can only look at and dream about - while at the same time having completely fresh legs for every weekend game. That’s the only reason Man Utd are currently just about hanging on in the top half and a solid four points away from dropping out of the top 10.

If you ask the average Newcastle fan, I’m pretty sure Man Utd aren’t a club they have particularly impressive thoughts about. The focus is aimed forward toward much bigger clubs that Newcastle want to compare themselves with in the future.

